2026-03-21 | Number of Unique BSTs for Each Root

	Question
For each index i, return number of unique BSTs when arr[i] is root.

	Approach
1.	First, sort the array (BST depends on relative ordering).
2.	Let n = size of array.
3.	If arr[i] is root:
		left subtree size = i  
		right subtree size = n - i - 1  

4.	Number of BSTs:
		Catalan(left) × Catalan(right)

5.	Precompute Catalan numbers:
		C[0] = 1  
		C[n] = sum(C[i] * C[n-i-1])

6.	Build answer using:
		ans[i] = C[i] * C[n-i-1]

	Time Complexity
	O(n²) (for Catalan computation)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    vector<long long> countBST(vector<int>& arr) {

        int n = arr.size();
        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());

        vector<long long> catalan(n + 1, 0);
        catalan[0] = catalan[1] = 1;

        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
                catalan[i] += catalan[j] * catalan[i - j - 1];
            }
        }

        vector<long long> ans(n);

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            ans[i] = catalan[i] * catalan[n - i - 1];
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
The number of BSTs depends only on the **count of nodes**, not their actual values.  
So once sorted, each element’s position determines:
		how many nodes go left and right → leading to Catalan multiplication.
